meowiitten 2025-09-20 10:35 p.m.
The relevant background of the motion does a good job with describing the allegations in the complaint, but I'll just copy and paste the general part of that here:
On July 31, 2025, WooleyMcNoble—acting in his capacity as President and CEO of
Meyerhauser Logging, LLC and Chairman of the Columbia First Party—approved a financial
transaction to launder the proceeds of illicit drug sales through a falsified invoice. (clearlysens Aff. ¶¶
III(1)–(4); Ex. A, D) The transaction originated from Columbia First Party member “OftenNews,”
who had acquired approximately $1,000,000 UCD through the illegal manufacture and sale of the
controlled substance Jarniwanus. (clearlysens Aff. ¶¶ III(1)–(4); Ex. B1–B2). According to
contemporaneous communications, CantBr_eathalyseNopy, an officer of Meyerhauser Logging,
proposed that the full amount be disguised as a “Startup investment” and processed via an invoice
to Meyerhauser Logging. (Ex. E; clearlysens Aff. ¶¶ III(1)–(4)).

Essentially, the only thing this court needs to determine on this partial motion for summary judgment is whether the invoice that was kept and maintained by Meyerhauser Logging was (1) false or misleading, and (2) used in the conduct of business. Conduct of business means the invoice was used as part of Meyerhauser Logging’s ordinary business practices in general. The invoice in question is Exhibit E, which I will send here below:
meowiitten 2025-09-20 10:37 p.m.
Case law on N.Y. Exec. Law Section 63(12) defines “conduct of business” as just meaning that the invoice (or document) was used as part of Meyerhauser Logging’s ordinary business practices in general. That element is clearly satisfied since the invoice itself was maintained by Meyerhauser. And an invoice is an instrument that is used as part of ordinary business practices.
meowiitten 2025-09-20 10:41 p.m.
Now, back to the first element: whether the invoice was false or misleading. That element is also clearly satisfied both by the record evidence (refer to the supporting exhibits cited in the “Relevant Background” section above) and by a facial reading of the complaint. The "startup investment” was not an investment at all, but laundered funds sourced through drug trafficking, which were then funneled through Meyerhauser Logging and documented by that invoice. And even if it was an "investment," it was never reported to the Department of State in a quarterly financial statement which is required under Title 4.

meowiitten 2025-09-20 11:18 p.m.
Yes, it was not an investment at all. The invoice was false. That should be clear from the record evidence. And even then, if it had been a lawful investment, it was required to be reported -- but it was not.

I should also clarify that, for purposes of § 8223, and you may choose whether or not to incorporate this understanding, § 63(12) interprets fraudulent conduct as any act, or series of acts, that has "the capacity or tendency to deceive, or creates an atmosphere conducive to fraud.” People v. Applied Card Sys., Inc., 27 A.D.3d 104, 106 (3d Dep’t 2005), aff’d on other grounds, 11 N.Y.3d 105 (2008) (quoting People v. Gen. Elec. Co., 302 A.D.2d 314 (1st Dep’t 2003)).

Certainly, funneling drug money and disguising it as a lawful investment is either deceptive in itself or, at minimum, creates an atmosphere conducive to fraud.

meowiitten 2025-09-20 11:25 p.m.
No. Money obtained unlawfully cannot be transformed into a lawful “investment.” I could try to find a case that maybeeeeeee says that, but I'd either never find it, or I'd be looking all night. Even without an express representation, disguising drug proceeds as capital contributions is inherently fraudulent laundering, which falls squarely within § 8223/§ 63(12)’s definition of fraud -- it is either deceptive or creates an atmosphere conducive to fraud.

meowiitten 2025-09-20 11:42 p.m.
We do not need to establish common-law fraud elements such as intent or reliance to establish liability under § 8223/§ 63(12). See People v. Apple Health & Sports Clubs, Ltd., 206 A.D.2d 266, 267 (1st Dep’t 1994), appeal denied, 84 N.Y.2d 1004 (1994); State v. Ford Motor Co., 136 A.D.2d 154, 158 (3d Dep’t 1988), aff’d, 74 N.Y.2d 495 (1989). Fraud is established where Defendants engaged in conduct that had the capacity or tendency to deceive, or created an atmosphere conducive to fraud. See People v. Gen. Elec. Co., 302 A.D.2d 314 (1st Dep’t 2003). Here, the fraudulent invoice was maintained and used by Meyerhauser as part of its business operations, and then furthered the laundering of funds through Columbia First. That conduct is both fraudulent and, because it facilitated subsequent laundering transactions, “repeated or persistent” under the statute.
